l = len(mpg_data[(mpg_data['hp'] > hp_Q3+(1.5*hp_IQR)) | (mpg_data['acc']> acc_Q3+(acc_IQR*1.5)) | (mpg_data['acc'] < acc_Q1-(acc_IQR*1.5))])
print('There are {} outliers in total.'.format(l))

There are 19 outliers in total.
We should consider the reason for these outliers. By doing a little research online, we can see if the outliers are actual values or because of errors in making entries.¶
Further we observe that all the outlier in hp belong to the same categories i.e. 8 cylindered cars from Origin 1. So we can believe that a trend exist here and these are actual values. Let us leave this column for now.¶
Imputing values for outliers in this data set can be tricky as the values of acceleration can completely depend on type of car (8 cylindered are usualy big heavy cars while 4 cylindered are smaller and lighter cars). So choosing to directly impute the values with mean or median of the column may not be a wise thihng to do.¶
We can employ one of the following two strats:¶
  1. Since the outliers are only 19 (~4.5% of the entire data), we may choose to drop them as we don't want to impute the values of acceleration and hp which can have an impact on mpg. Let us do this once we build our model.
  2. If we want to impute, we can choose to cap the data with upper and lower quartiles.
Let us go with the second strat for acc column¶
In [31]:
mpg_data['acc']= mpg_data['acc'].clip(lower= mpg_data['acc'].quantile(0.05), upper= mpg_data['acc'].quantile(0.95))
All our categorical variables are already labeled. We can leave them at that or use one-hot encoding if we want to remove the affect of numbers on mpg prediction.¶

Proportions¶
Let us ready two functions that can give the overall proportion of a categorical variable and the propotion of a categorical vairable with respect to another categorical variable.¶
In [57]:
def OverallProportion (col_name, prop_of):
    x = mpg_data[col_name].value_counts()
    return round(x[prop_of]/sum(x), 4)
    
def GroupbyProportion(group_by, col_name, group_of, prop_of): 
    x = mpg_data.groupby(group_by)[col_name].value_counts()
    return round(x[group_of][prop_of]/sum(x[group_of]), 4)

#col_name - which column we need proportion of
#prop_of - which value in the col_name we need the proportion of
#group_by - which column to group by 
#group_of - wrt which value of the group the proportion is required

In [93]:
def hue_regplot(data, x, y, hue, palette=None, **kwargs):
    regplots = []
    levels = data[hue].unique()
    
    for key in levels:
        regplots.append(sns.regplot(x=x,y=y,data=data[data[hue] == key],**kwargs))
    
    return regplots

The performance of individual models is way worse than the overall model. This is most like due to splitting the data further which has induced curse of dimensionality.¶
In this particular case, splitting the data into clusters to do regression analysis for mpg is not helpful. It affects the performance of the models in a negative manner¶
¶
But there is another aspect to consider here:¶
Let us compare the co-efficents of all 4 models¶

It is very clear that the coefficients are different for each cluster. This implies that the relationship between mpg and various features are different for different clusters. So it is the correct strategy to form clusters and apply regression model to individual clusters.¶

However, since the lack of 'quantity' of data, we are unable to use to this strategy as splitting the data further introduces curse of dimensionality into the datasets.¶

Question 6 - Improvisation:¶
In [116]:
# Detailed suggestions or improvements or on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the company 
# to perform a better data analysis in future.
Firstly the model might perform better if there is a lot more data available ($Quantity$ of data). We observed some outliers in the data in regards to columns hp and acc, this may be due to unreliable source for data collection or due to entries of some rare cars that affected the $Quality$ of the data. $Variety$ and $Velocity$ does not impact much in this particular case as we are not doing any real time analyses.¶
Speaking of the models used, from the early multivariate analyses, we observed that the mpg is strongly correlated to weight, horsepower and displacement.We also observed from the graphs (regplots) drawn after the clustering is done and also the initial pairplots, that this relationship is $not$ $linear$ and hence we may expect to see better results if we use a model other than linear regression (like $quadriatic$ $linear$ $regression$).¶

def impute_values_SVM(data):
    nan_data = data[data['Quality'].isna()].drop('Quality', axis = 1)
    missing_data = svc_model.predict(nan_data)
    nan_data['Quality'] = missing_data
    data = data.dropna()
    final_df = pd.concat([data, nan_data])
    return final_df.sort_index()

def impute_values_KMeans(data):
    nan_data = data[data['Quality'].isna()].drop('Quality', axis = 1)
    nan_data_z = sc.transform(nan_data)
    nan_data['Quality'] = km_model_wine.predict(nan_data_z)
    nan_data.Quality.replace(0, 'Quality B', inplace = True)
    nan_data.Quality.replace(1, 'Quality A', inplace = True)
    data = data.dropna()
    final_df = pd.concat([data, nan_data])
    return final_df.sort_index()
Just pass the dataset with missing values into this function and it will return the dataset with imputed values based on prediction using K Means¶

Suggestion

In the future it would be helpful to have more data to work with. We have built a model using only 43 data points. Since we used K Means model it is advisable to scale our data but in this case, scaling can result in sampling errors as there are too few entries.¶
This is most likely to lead to overfitting of the model and may not be accurate in imputing the correct values into the missing data.¶
Since we have labeled data we can also use SVM (or some other supervised learning method) to train our model.¶
